The mobility of people and ideas around the world has generated new global citizens who transcend conventional boundaries of identity and place. This course explores how the rights and responsibilities of global citizens should be defined, as well as the impact of individual decisions on the global scale. In addition, it explores the role of English in global communication. Class texts include films such as Pocahontas, Beneath Clouds, Life and Debt, and Miracle at St. Anna.&#8232;

&#8232;Most students reported the course content as “stimulating” and “interesting.” As with most writing seminars, students did not like the “restrictive” and “tedious” nature of the assignments. However, one student reported, “Despite some problems with the writing seminar as a whole, this class was entertaining and well run.” &#8232;

Students had mixed reviews about Professor Pagan Teitelbaum. One student said she “spent too much time advancing her own agenda,” while another called her “equal parts strict and kind.” However, for the most part students appreciated her “enthusiasm for the subject” and ability to engage students in the topic. &#8232;

Writing assignments include drafting and revision of brief position papers, peer review, online writing, and midterm and final portfolios. Students reported a lot of “busy work,” though there was not as much reading because the textual focus was on films. The course fulfills the Writing Requirement.

